Figure 2 shows a histogram of the sequence distribution of the differences between observed and computed 13Cα chemical shifts, Δca,i, obtained with Eqs. (1) and (2) for the NAB ensemble. Here, we investigate sequential nearest-neighbor effects on the calculated shifts.


In the standard calculation procedure of Vila et al. (2007b) each residue Xxx has Gly residues as sequential neighbors in the model peptides Ac-Gly-Xxx-Gly-NMe. For further refinement of the predictions we are interested in determining the magnitudes of the changes in Δca,i that may occur if the glycines in the model peptides are replaced by the actual nearest-neighbor residues in the protein sequence. Thus, we computed 13Cα chemical shifts for each residue Xxx of the 20 NAB conformers using the two model peptides Ac-Gly-Yyy-Xxx-Gly-NMe and Ac-Gly-Xxx-Yyy-Gly-NMe, where Yyy designates the preceding or subsequent residue-type, and the dihedral angles for the dipeptides -Yyy-Xxx- and -Xxx-Yyy- were taken from the 20 NMR conformers.

